                  <li class="program-course">
            <a href="/study/2014-2015/courses/phil-237" class="program-course-title">
              PHIL 237 Contemporary Moral Issues (3 credits)              <!---->            </a>
            <div class="program-course-description">
              <div class="program-course-description-inner">
                <div id="node-33173" class=" clearfix">
  
  
  
  <div class="meta">
    <p>Offered by: Philosophy (<a href="/study/2014-2015/node/607">Faculty of Arts</a>)</p>
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      Philosophy              : An introductory discussion of central ethical questions (the value of persons, or the relationship of rights and utilities, for example) through the investigation of currently disputed social and political issues. Specific issues to be discussed may include pornography and censorship, affirmative action, civil disobedience, punishment, abortion, and euthanasia.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              Winter 2015          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:                        Kristin Voigt (Winter)                  </p>

    
      </div>

