          </li>
                  <li class="program-course">
            <a href="/study/2014-2015/courses/mujz-160" class="program-course-title">
              MUJZ 160 Jazz Materials 1 (3 credits)              *            </a>
            <div class="program-course-description">
              <div class="program-course-description-inner">
                <div id="node-31434" class=" clearfix">
  
  
  
  <div class="meta">
    <p>Offered by: Performance (<a href="/study/2014-2015/node/613">Schulich School of Music</a>)</p>
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      Jazz Studies              : Fundamental aural and theoretical skills associated with the jazz idiom. Nomenclature, chord construction, chord/scale relationships, harmonic progression, circle of 5ths, simple turnarounds, simple substitution, symmetrical scales and chord relationships, voice leading.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              Fall 2014          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:                        Paul Rushka (Fall)                  </p>

    
          <ul class="catalog-notes">
              <li>4 hours</li>
              <li>Prerequisite: none. Open to non-jazz majors, space permitting, but not for elective credit in B.Mus. or Artist Diploma programs</li>
            </ul>
      </div>

  </div> <!-- /.node -->
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>
                  <li class="program-course">
            <a href="/study/2014-2015/courses/mujz-161" class="program-course-title">
              MUJZ 161 Jazz Materials 2 (3 credits)              *            </a>
            <div class="program-course-description">
              <div class="program-course-description-inner">
                <div id="node-31436" class=" clearfix">
  
  
  
  <div class="meta">
    <p>Offered by: Performance (<a href="/study/2014-2015/node/613">Schulich School of Music</a>)</p>
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      Jazz Studies              : Simple and advanced substitution, borrowed chords, reharmonisation, modes of harmonic minor and melodic minor diatonic systems, unresolved tensions, odd and infrequent modulations, mixed two-five-ones, introduction to polychords, slashchords and non-functional harmony.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              Winter 2015          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:              There are no professors associated with this course for the 2014-2015 academic year.          </p>

    
          <ul class="catalog-notes">
              <li>4 hours</li>
              <li>Prerequisite: MUJZ 160. Open to non-jazz majors, space permitting, but not for elective credit in B.Mus. or Artist Diploma programs </li>
            </ul>
      </div>

  </div> <!-- /.node -->
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>
                </ul>
      
      
                <h4>Natural Sciences</h4>

    
              <p>Students may choose up to 12 credits from this list.</p>
    
              <ul class="program-set">
                  <li class="program-course">
            <a href="/study/2014-2015/courses/atoc-181" class="program-course-title">
              ATOC 181 Introduction to Atmospheric Science (3 credits)              <!---->            </a>
            <div class="program-course-description">
              <div class="program-course-description-inner">
                <div id="node-18494" class=" clearfix">
  
  
  
  <div class="meta">
    <p>Offered by: Atmospheric &amp; Oceanic Sciences (<a href="/study/2014-2015/node/615">Faculty of Science</a>)</p>
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      Atmospheric &amp; Oceanic Sciences              : A survey of the Earth's atmosphere, weather and climate system. Topics include the fundamental processes that determine interactions between the atmosphere, ocean and biosphere; anthropogenic effects such as global warming, the ozone hole and acid rain; a perspective on future climate change.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              Fall 2014, Winter 2015          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:                        Gerard Szejwach (Fall)                  Andreas Zuend (Winter)                  </p>

    
          <ul class="catalog-notes">
              <li>Fall and Winter</li>
              <li>3 hours lecture</li>
              <li>Restriction: Not open to students who have taken ATOC 210, ATOC 214, ENVB 301 or NRSC 201.</li>
            </ul>
      </div>

  </div> <!-- /.node -->
              </div>
